SSH keys — the right way to authenticate.

Password authentication over SSH works, but it has two real problems: passwords are guessable, and you have to type one every single time. SSH keys solve both. A key is a cryptographic pair of files. There's a private key, which stays on your machine and is never, ever shared, and a public key, which you copy to every server you want to reach. When you connect, the server hands you a challenge that only the holder of the matching private key can answer. No password is ever sent over the wire, and you don't have to type one.

To generate a key, the modern recommended algorithm is Ed25519, which is fast, secure, and produces small keys. You run ssh-keygen dash-t ed25519, and optionally dash-capital-C with a comment like your email, just to label it. That produces two files. The private one is tilde-slash-dot-ssh-slash-id-underscore-ed25519, which you never share. The public one has the same name with a dot-pub on the end, and that one is safe to copy anywhere. Now, when it prompts you for a passphrase, always set one on a real machine. The passphrase encrypts the private key on disk, so a stolen key file is useless without it, and, as we'll see next section, the agent means you only type that passphrase once per session. If you're stuck supporting an ancient system that can't do Ed25519, fall back to RSA with at least three thousand seventy-two bits.

To install your public key onto a server, the easy way is ssh-copy-id, user-at-host. That appends your public key to the authorized-keys file in the server's dot-ssh directory, creating it with the right permissions if needed. After that, ssh to that host logs you straight in, no password.

Finally, a warning that bites everyone at least once: SSH is deliberately strict about file permissions, and it will flatly refuse to use your keys if they're too open. So your dot-ssh directory must be mode seven hundred, and your private key and your authorized-keys file must both be mode six hundred, readable and writable only by you. If you ever see a "permissions are too open" error, that is always what it is; fix it with chmod, and you're back in business.
